Wreck of bark (Windward) in front of dock. M. R. Maddock's building left in front of trestle. R. H. Denny, North side of Union Street. Young Naturalist's first home, rear of A. A. Denny home."

The 1891 Ballard City Directory contains the follow entry: ""Begg Wm D, grocer, w s Ballard ave bet 2d and 3d aves, res same."" The Ballard Wine House, located at 2nd Ave. and Ballard Ave. is visible in the distance on the left.

title: Central School faculty on opening day, May 7, 1883

title: Princess Angeline's home, 1902
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Princess Angeline's "Palace" and last home, where she died about 1891. Located on the north side of Stewart Street, half a block west of First Avenue. Land donated by A.A. Denny, lumber by Henry Yesler and building erected by Amos Brown." Paul Dorpat's blog post "Seattle Now & Then: Finding Kikisoblu (aka ‘Princess Angeline’)" places the site of the home closer to Pike St. and Western Ave.

title: View north from Volunteer Park Water Tower, ca. 1915

title: Babette Schwabacher Gatzert, ca. 1880
description: From HistoryLink article "Gatzert, Bailey (1829-1893:" "Babette Schwabacher, Gatzert's wife, was a founding member of the Ladies Relief Society (now Seattle Children's Home). Established in 1884, it was Seattle's first charity organization. The Gatzerts' home, on 3rd Avenue and James Street, was a center of social activity and hospitality. Though the property is now in the city's core, the Gatzerts kept a cow and cultivated an orchard. Their closest neighbors were the Henry Yeslers. In 1880 when Rutherford B. Hayes (1822-1893) achieved the distinction of being the first president to cross the Rockies, the Gatzerts entertained him at their home."

title: Territorial University, ca. 1870
description: The main Territorial University Building was constructed in 1861.

title: Streetcars at Boren Ave. and Stewart St., ca. 1910
description: According to the 1917 Sanborn Fire Insurance map, the Norwegian-Danish Methodist Episcopal Church appears at the corner of Boren Ave. and Stewart St. behind the streetcar.

title: David Denny aboard the Rainier Power and Railway Company's streetcar, 1892
description: David T. Denny appears at the front of the car on the right. David Denny, Jr. appears at the end of the car. Denny, Sr. was an investor of the Rainier Power and Railway Company but lost many of his investments in the financial crisis of 1893. The photograph is taken at the south end of Lake Union. The streetcar route ran along Eastlake Avenue and across the Latona Bridge to the University District.

title: View NE from Beacon Hill, ca. 1880
intersection: 10th Ave. S. and S. Dearborn St.

title: Everett McCrady, September 1953
description: Transcribed from photograph: "A fast getaway - Ev. McCrady, former Tacoma bowler, rolled a 288 score in the first game he ever bowled in a Seattle league. McCrady moved to Seattle this summer to work for Boeing, rolling his big game on the opening night of the Boeing Major League. He followed through with two more good games for a 666 series."

title: 45th St. Theatre, 1937
description: The 45th St. Theatre (originally called the Paramount Theatre) opened in 1921. It was renamed the 45th Street Theatre in the 1930s and then the Guild 45th in the 1960s. The theater closed in 2017. The theater's marquee advertises "The Frame Up" as the featured film. The movie premiered in 1937.

title: Sarah Truax, February 1904
description: Transcribed from photograph: ""Feb. 1904. Autog. Sep. 30, 1938. Sarah Truax. Stage actress. Donna Roma in The Eternal City."" Truax had a successful career staring in touring shows. She and her husband moved to Spokane, Washington in 1912 and to Seattle in 1927 where she remained active with community theatre.

title: Washington State Building, 1909
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Alaska Yukon Pacific Exposition, 1909. Washington State Building. Photo by Lowman and Hanford. Howard and Galloway, architects. Used as University of Washington Library, 1909-1929. Used for the Washington State Museum after 1930. Gift of Thomas Pelly, 1972."
subjects: Washington State Building (Alaska-Yukon-Pacific Exposition, 1909, Seattle, Wash.)

title: Paramount Theatre on N. 45th St., 1925
description: The Paramount Theatre opened in 1921. It was later renamed the 45th Street Theatre in the 1930s and then the Guild 45th in the 1960s. The theater closed in 2017. The theater's marquee advertises ""The Pony Express"" as the featured film. The movie premiered in 1925.

title: View SE from 4th Ave. and Seneca St., 1883
description: Central School (labeled as number 1) and the Providence Hospital (labeled as number 2) appear at the top center of the photograph.

title: Interlake School, ca. 1904
description: The school opened in 1904 and closed in 1971. After it's closure as an elementary school, it operated as an annex for Lincoln High School. The building was designated as a city landmark in 1981. In 1983, the name of the building was changed to Wallingford Center, a retail space with apartments on the upper level.

title: Providence Hospital, ca. 1889
description: Transcribed from photograph: ""Providence Hospital was established in Seattle 1877 by the Sisters of Charity, first established under contract in the old county hospital, or building which passed as such, located on the Duwamish river in what later became Georgetown. In 1878 they bought the block at 5th and Madison on which the building shown in this foot was erected. The first section built is shown as being the little left-hand corner. Next came the center section in 1882 and a few years later the first section, completing the structure as shown. This foot was evidently taken in 1889 or 1890, before the Madison Street cable line was placed in operation in 1890. The last and present Providence Hospital, at 17th and Jefferson Street, was built in 1911 and the old property sold. In recent years the government took over this original hospital block and now have erected a magnificent Federal Court house building on the site.""

title: King Street Station, 1907
description: During the early 1900s, there was increasing interest in connecting railroads with Seattle. The high demand and competition between railways resulted in two railway stations being built directly next to each other at 4th Avenue and Jackson Street. King Street Station (which is depicted here) was constructed in 1906 and can be distinguished by its tower. Union Station, originally known as the Oregon and Washington Station, was constructed in 1911. (Alternative names for Union Station include the Union Depot and the Northern Pacific Great Northern Depot.) Both stations were sometimes referred to as ""union stations"" or ""union depots"" due to the fact that multiple railroad lines were shared within the same terminal.

title: John Ross, ca. 1870
description: Ross was an early Seattle pioneer who held land claims in the North Queen Anne and Fremont areas. His wife, Mary Ross, opened the neighborhood's first school in 1873.

title: Zoe Stetson holding flag from Civil War at the South School Columbus Day celebration, ca. 1940
description: Transcribed from photograph: "A "Civil War flag" belonging to the Stetson family, displayed first at South School's "Columbus Day" exercises. In the picture are left to right, Floyd Croft, Dell [?], Frank Frink, and Zoe Renninger Stetson, owner, holding the precious flag." The South School closed in 1909 due to the Jackson St. regrade. Bailey Gatzert was built on the same site as the former South School in 1921 but it is unclear if this is the location where the photograph was taken.

Clarence E. Duggan, ca. 1950
description: Duggan (likely the man on the left) played baseball for American and Canadian baseball leagues in the early 1900s. The men are walking outside of a Lundquist-Lilly store. According to the 1951 City Directory, Lundquist-Lilly had two locations, one at 317 Pike St. and one at 1427 4th Ave. The 317 Pike St. location has been provided as the most likely photograph location.

title: Suzzallo Library, April 20, 1926
Johnson home at 5th Ave. and Seneca St., ca. 1884
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Prof. J.B. Johnsen and his wife [Mary] at their home on Seneca St. and south of the old University. Taken in early '80's." The 1885 City Directory lists an O.B. Johnson working as a professor at the Territorial University and residing at the SE corner of 5th Ave. and Seneca St. Orson B. Johnson first started teaching science at the University in 1882. Johnson Hall on the present University of Washington campus bears his name.
